# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chi-router-go
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:chi-router-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware often enables interoperability between applications that run on different operating systems, by supplying services so the application can exchange data in a standards-based way.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware sits "in the middle" between application software that may be working on different operating systems.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] It is similar to the middle layer of a three-tier single system architecture, except that it is stretched across multiple systems or applications.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Examples include EAI software, telecommunications software, transaction monitors, and messaging-and-queueing software.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] The distinction between operating system and middleware functionality is, to some extent, arbitrary.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] While core kernel functionality can only be provided by the operating system itself, some functionality previously provided by separately sold middleware is now integrated in operating systems.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] A typical example is the TCP/IP stack for telecommunications, nowadays included virtually in every operating system.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware is defined as software that provides a link between separate software applications.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] It is sometimes referred to as plumbing because it connects two applications and passes data between them.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware allows data contained in one database to be accessed through another.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] This makes it particularly useful for enterprise application integration and data integration tasks.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] It also facilitated distributed processing, the connection of multiple applications to create a larger application, usually over a network.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] when compared to the operating system and network services.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware offers some unique technological advantages for business and industry.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] For example, traditional database systems are usually deployed in closed environments where users access the system only via a restricted network or intranet (e.g., an enterprise’s internal network).
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] With the phenomenal growth of the World Wide Web, users can access virtually any database for which they have proper access rights from anywhere in the world.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware addresses the problem of varying levels of interoperability among different database structures.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware facilitates transparent access to legacy database management systems (DBMSs) or applications via a web server without regard to database-specific characteristics.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Businesses frequently use middleware applications to link information from departmental databases, such as payroll, sales, and accounting, or databases housed in multiple geographic locations.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] In the highly competitive healthcare community, laboratories make extensive use of middleware applications for data mining, laboratory information system (LIS) backup, and to combine systems during hospital mergers.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware helps bridge the gap between separate LISs in a newly formed healthcare network following a hospital buyout.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware can help software developers avoid having to write application programming interfaces (API) for every control program, by serving as an independent programming interface for their applications.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] For Future Internet network operation through traffic monitoring in multi-domain scenarios, using mediator tools (middleware) is a powerful help since they allow operators, searchers and service providers to supervise Quality of service and analyse eventual failures in telecommunication services.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Finally, e-commerce uses middleware to assist in handling rapid and secure transactions over many different types of computer environments.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] In short, middleware has become a critical element across a broad range of industries, thanks to its ability to bring together resources across dissimilar networks or computing platforms.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] In 2004 members of the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) carried out a study of Middleware with respect to system integration in broadcast environments.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] This involved system design engineering experts from 10 major European broadcasters working over a 12-month period to understand the effect of predominantly software-based products to media production and broadcasting system design techniques.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] The resulting reports Tech 3300 and Tech 3300s were published and are freely available from the EBU web site.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Message-oriented middleware (MOM) is middleware where transactions or event notifications are delivered between disparate systems or components by way of messages, often via an enterprise messaging system.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] With MOM, messages sent to the client are collected and stored until they are acted upon, while the client continues with other processing.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] software may queue, duplicate, translate and deliver messages to disparate systems or components in a messaging system.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Intelligent Middleware (IMW) provides real-time intelligence and event management through intelligent agents.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] The IMW manages the real-time processing of high volume sensor signals and turns these signals into intelligent and actionable business information.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] The actionable information is then delivered in end-user power dashboards to individual users or is pushed to systems within or outside the enterprise.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] It is able to support various heterogeneous types of hardware and software and provides an API for interfacing with external systems.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] It should have a highly scalable, distributed architecture which embeds intelligence throughout the network to transform raw data systematically into actionable and relevant knowledge.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] It can also be packaged with tools to view and manage operations and build advanced network applications most effectively.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Content-centric middleware offers a simple *provider-consumer* abstraction through which applications can issue requests for uniquely identified content, without worrying about where or how it is obtained.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Juno is one example, which allows applications to generate content requests associated with high-level delivery requirements.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] The middleware then adapts the underlying delivery to access the content from sources that are best suited to matching the requirements.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] This is therefore similar to Publish/subscribe middleware, as well as the Content-centric networking paradigm.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware enables a client to use services running on remote systems.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware, it is possible for applications to send objects and request services in an object-oriented system.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] is middleware between applications and database servers.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] integration interface that operates between embedded applications, the embedded operating system, and external applications.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliance is a generic term referring to any form of middleware that manages policy rules.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] They can mediate between data owners or producers, data aggregators, and data users.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Among heterogeneous institutional systems or networks they may be used to enforce, reconcile, and monitor agreed information management policies and laws across systems (or between jurisdictions) with divergent information policies or needs.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliances support policy-based information management processes by enabling rules-based processing, selective disclosure, and accountability and oversight.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] IBM, Red Hat, Oracle Corporation and Microsoft are some of the vendors that provide middleware software.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Vendors such as Axway, SAP, TIBCO, Informatica, Objective Interface Systems, Pervasive, ScaleOut Software and webMethods were specifically founded to provide more niche middleware solutions.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Groups such as the Apache Software Foundation, OpenSAF, the ObjectWeb Consortium (now OW2) and OASIS' AMQP encourage the development of open source middleware.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Microsoft .NET "Framework" architecture is essentially "Middleware" with typical middleware functions distributed between the various products, with most inter-computer interaction by industry standards, open APIs or RAND software licence.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] Solace provides middleware in purpose-built hardware for implementations that may experience scale.
[src:chi-router-go/middleware-distributed-applications] StormMQ provides Message Oriented Middleware as a service.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:chi-router-go/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In packet switching networks, routing is the higher-level decision-making that directs network packets from their source toward their destination through intermediate network nodes by specific packet forwarding mechanisms.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Packet forwarding is the transit of network packets from one network interface to another.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Intermediate nodes are typically network hardware devices such as routers, gateways, firewalls, or switches.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] General-purpose computers also forward packets and perform routing, although they have no specially optimized hardware for the task.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The routing process usually directs forwarding on the basis of routing tables.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Routing tables maintain a record of the routes to various network destinations.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Routing tables may be specified by an administrator, learned by observing network traffic or built with the assistance of routing protocols.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Routing, in a narrower sense of the term, often refers to IP routing and is contrasted with bridging.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] IP routing assumes that network addresses are structured and that similar addresses imply proximity within the network.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Structured addresses allow a single routing table entry to represent the route to a group of devices.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In large networks, structured addressing (routing, in the narrow sense) outperforms unstructured addressing (bridging).
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Routing has become the dominant form of addressing on the Internet.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Bridging is still widely used within local area networks.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Unicast is the dominant form of message delivery on the Internet.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This article focuses on unicast routing algorithms.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] With static routing, small networks may use manually configured routing tables.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Larger networks have complex topologies that can change rapidly, making the manual construction of routing tables unfeasible.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Nevertheless, most of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) uses pre-computed routing tables, with fallback routes if the most direct route becomes blocked (see routing in the PSTN).
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Dynamic routing attempts to solve this problem by constructing routing tables automatically, based on information carried by routing protocols, allowing the network to act nearly autonomously in avoiding network failures and blockages.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Examples of dynamic-routing protocols and algorithms include Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Distance vector algorithms use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This approach assigns a *cost* number to each of the links between each node in the network.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Nodes send information from point A to point B via the path that results in the lowest *total cost* (i.e., the sum of the costs of the links between the nodes used).
[src:chi-router-go/routing] When a node first starts, it only knows of its immediate neighbors and the direct cost involved in reaching them.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The neighboring nodes examine this information and compare it to what they already know; anything that represents an improvement on what they already have, they insert in their own table.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Over time, all the nodes in the network discover the best next hop and total cost for all destinations.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] When a network node goes down, any nodes that used it as their next hop discard the entry and convey the updated routing information to all adjacent nodes, which in turn repeat the process.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Eventually, all the nodes in the network receive the updates and discover new paths to all the destinations that do not involve the down node.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] When applying link-state algorithms, a graphical map of the network is the fundamental data used for each node.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] To produce its map, each node floods the entire network with information about the other nodes it can connect to.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Each node then independently assembles this information into a map.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Using this map, each router independently determines the least-cost path from itself to every other node using a standard shortest paths algorithm such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The result is a tree graph rooted at the current node, such that the path through the tree from the root to any other node is the least-cost path to that node.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This tree then serves to construct the routing table, which specifies the best next hop to get from the current node to any other node.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] A link-state routing algorithm optimized for mobile ad hoc networks is the optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:chi-router-go/routing] OLSR is proactive; it uses Hello and Topology Control (TC) messages to discover and disseminate link-state information through the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Using Hello messages, each node discovers 2-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:chi-router-go/routing] MPRs distinguish OLSR from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Distance vector and link-state routing are both intra-domain routing protocols.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] They are used inside an autonomous system, but not between autonomous systems.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Both of these routing protocols become intractable in large networks and cannot be used in inter-domain routing.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Distance vector routing is subject to instability if there are more than a few hops in the domain.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Link-state routing needs significant resources to calculate routing tables.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] It also creates heavy traffic due to flooding.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Path-vector routing is used for inter-domain routing.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] It is similar to distance vector routing.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Path-vector routing assumes that one node (there can be many) in each autonomous system acts on behalf of the entire autonomous system.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This node is called the *speaker node.* The speaker node creates a routing table and advertises it to neighboring speaker nodes in neighboring autonomous systems.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The idea is the same as distance vector routing, except that only speaker nodes in each autonomous system can communicate with each other.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The speaker node advertises the path, not the metric, of the nodes in its autonomous system or other autonomous systems.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The path-vector routing algorithm is similar to the distance vector algorithm in the sense that each border router advertises the destinations it can reach to its neighboring router.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] However, instead of advertising networks in terms of a destination and the distance to that destination, networks are advertised as destination addresses and path descriptions to reach those destinations.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The path, expressed in terms of the domains (or confederations) traversed so far, is carried in a special path attribute that records the sequence of routing domains through which the reachability information has passed.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] A route is defined as a pairing between a destination and the attributes of the path to that destination, thus the name, path-vector routing.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The routers receive a vector that contains paths to a set of destinations.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Path selection involves applying a routing metric to multiple routes to select (or predict) the best route.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Most routing algorithms use only one network path at a time.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Multipath routing and specifically equal-cost multi-path routing techniques enable the use of multiple alternative paths.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In computer networking, the metric is computed by a routing algorithm, and can cover information such as bandwidth, network delay, hop count, path cost, load, maximum transmission unit, reliability, and communication cost.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The routing table stores only the best possible routes, while link-state or topological databases may store all other information as well.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] *Metric*: When comparing routes learned via the same routing protocol, a lower metric is preferred.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Metrics cannot be compared between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] *Administrative distance*: When comparing route table entries from different sources, such as different routing protocols and static configuration, a lower administrative distance indicates a more reliable source and thus a preferred route.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Because a routing metric is specific to a given routing protocol, multi-protocol routers must use some external heuristic to select between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Cisco routers, for example, attribute a value known as the administrative distance to each route, where smaller administrative distances indicate routes learned from a protocol assumed to be more reliable.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] A local administrator can set up host-specific routes that provide more control over network usage, permit testing, and better overall security.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This is useful for debugging network connections or routing tables.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In some small systems, a single central device decides ahead of time the complete path of every packet.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In some other small systems, whichever edge device injects a packet into the network decides ahead of time the complete path of that particular packet.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In either case, the route-planning device needs to know a lot of information about what devices are connected to the network and how they are connected to each other.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Once it has this information, it can use an algorithm such as A* search algorithm to find the best path.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In high-speed systems, there are so many packets transmitted every second that it is infeasible for a single device to calculate the complete path for each and every packet.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Early high-speed systems dealt with this with circuit switching by setting up a path once for the first packet between some source and some destination; later packets between that same source and that same destination continue to follow the same path without recalculating until the circuit teardown.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Later high-speed systems inject packets into the network without any one device ever calculating a complete path for packets.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In large systems, there are so many connections between devices, and those connections change so frequently, that it is infeasible for any one device to even know how all the devices are connected to each other, much less calculate a complete path through them.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Such systems generally use next-hop routing.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Most systems use a deterministic dynamic routing algorithm.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] When a device chooses a path to a particular final destination, that device always chooses the same path to that destination until it receives information that makes it think some other path is better.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] A few routing algorithms do not use a deterministic algorithm to find the best link for a packet to get from its original source to its final destination.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Instead, to avoid congestion hot spots in packet systems, a few algorithms use a randomized algorithm—Valiant's paradigm—that routes a path to a randomly picked intermediate destination, and from there to its true final destination.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In many early telephone switches, a randomizer was often used to select the start of a path through a multistage switching fabric.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Depending on the application for which path selection is performed, different metrics can be used.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] For example, for web requests, one can use minimum latency paths to minimize web page load time, or for bulk data transfers, one can choose the least utilized path to balance load across the network and increase throughput.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] A popular path selection objective is to reduce the average completion times of traffic flows and the total network bandwidth consumption.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Recently, a path selection metric was proposed that computes the total number of bytes scheduled on the edges per path as a selection metric.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] An empirical analysis of several path selection metrics, including this new proposal, has been made available.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In some networks, routing is complicated by the fact that no single entity is responsible for selecting paths; instead, multiple entities are involved in selecting paths or even parts of a single path.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Complications or inefficiency can result if these entities choose paths to optimize their own objectives, which may conflict with the objectives of other participants.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] A classic example involves traffic in a road system, in which each driver picks a path that minimizes their travel time.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] With such routing, the equilibrium routes can be longer than optimal for all drivers.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In particular, Braess's paradox shows that adding a new road can *lengthen* travel times for all drivers.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In a single-agent model used, for example, for routing automated guided vehicles (AGVs) on a terminal, reservations are made for each vehicle to prevent simultaneous use of the same part of an infrastructure.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This approach is also referred to as context-aware routing.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The Internet is partitioned into autonomous systems (ASs) such as internet service providers (ISPs), each of which controls routes involving its network.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] First, AS-level paths are selected via the BGP protocol that produces a sequence of ASs through which packets flow.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Each AS may have multiple paths, offered by neighboring ASs, from which to choose.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] These routing decisions often correlate with business relationships with these neighboring ASs, which may be unrelated to path quality or latency.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Second, once an AS-level path has been selected, there are often multiple corresponding router-level paths to choose from.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This is due, in part, because two ISPs may be connected through multiple connections.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In choosing the single router-level path, it is common practice for each ISP to employ hot-potato routing: sending traffic along the path that minimizes the distance through the ISP's own network—even if that path lengthens the total distance to the destination.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] For example, consider two ISPs, *A* and *B*.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Each has a presence in New York, connected by a fast link with latency 5 ms—and each has a presence in London connected by a 5 ms link.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Suppose both ISPs have trans-Atlantic links that connect their two networks, but *A*'s link has latency 100 ms and *B*'s has latency 120 ms.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] When routing a message from a source in *A*'s London network to a destination in *B*'s New York network, *A* may choose to immediately send the message to *B* in London.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This saves *A* the work of sending it along an expensive trans-Atlantic link, but causes the message to experience latency 125 ms when the other route would have been 20 ms faster.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Additionally, a similar routing challenge can be observed in cellular networks, where different packets are destined for various endpoints, and each link exhibits varying spectral efficiency.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In this context, the selection of the *optimal* path involves considering latency and packet error rate.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] To address this, multiple independent entities, one for each base station, play a crucial role in path selection while striving to optimize overall network performance.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] A 2003 measurement study of Internet routes found that, between pairs of neighboring ISPs, more than 30% of paths have inflated latency due to hot-potato routing, with 5% of paths being delayed by at least 12 ms.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Inflation due to AS-level path selection, while substantial, was attributed primarily to BGP's lack of a mechanism to directly optimize for latency, rather than to selfish routing policies.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] It was also suggested that, were an appropriate mechanism in place, ISPs would be willing to cooperate to reduce latency rather than use hot-potato routing.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Such a mechanism was later published by the same authors, first for the case of two ISPs and then for the global case.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] As the Internet and IP networks have become mission critical business tools, there has been increased interest in techniques and methods to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation, flapping or downtime.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Monitoring routing in a network is achieved using route analytics tools and techniques.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] In networks where a logically centralized control is available over the forwarding state, for example, using software-defined networking, routing techniques can be used that aim to optimize global and network-wide performance metrics.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] This has been used by large internet companies that operate many data centers in different geographical locations attached using private optical links, examples of which include Microsoft's Global WAN, Facebook's Express Backbone, and Google's B4.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Global performance metrics to optimize include maximizing network utilization, minimizing traffic flow completion times, maximizing the traffic delivered prior to specific deadlines and reducing the completion times of flows.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] Work on the later over private WAN discusses modeling routing as a graph optimization problem by pushing all the queuing to the end-points.
[src:chi-router-go/routing] The authors also propose a heuristic to solve the problem efficiently while sacrificing negligible performance.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p02] Below are the latest statistics of the market share of all sites of the top web servers on the Internet by Netcraft.
[src:chi-router-go/web-server-p02] NOTE: (*) percentage rounded to integer number, because its decimal values are not publicly reported by source page (only its rounded value is reported in graph).
